\section{Learning objective}
The objectives of this experiment are to provide the student with an opportunity to:

\begin{itemize}
\item Gain additional experience with Matlab.
\item Create a simple program for data acquisition using toolbox and National Instrument's USB-6001/ NI My DAQ.
\item Become familiar with breadboards, wiring, digital multi-meters, oscilloscopes, function generators, and other basic laboratory equipment and skills.
\end{itemize}

\section{Equipment checklist}
\begin{itemize}
\item	Digital Multi-Meter (both handheld and table-top)
\item	DC Power Supply
\item	Function Generator
\item	Oscilloscope
\item	USB Data Acquisition Device ( NI MyDAQ) 
\item	Breadboard – JE25 / Digilent
\item	Wire Kit 
\item	Needle Nose Pliers
\item	Wire Stripper
\item	Screwdriver
\item	Circuit Component Kit
\item	BNC T-Connectors
\end{itemize}

\section{Introduction}
In this experiment, you will compare the measured signals from multiple sources including: an oscilloscope, a digital multi-meter, a table-top digital multi-meter, and the NI-MyDAQ data acquisition device to view both DC and AC signals through the voltage divider circuit. 

A typical components of AC signal is shown in figure \ref{fig:demoSignal}. As observed in the figure the DC-offset component is the offset of the signal from reference (i.e., zero volts) and $V_{pp}$ is the difference between the maximum and minimum voltage in the AC signal.
\begin{figure}[!h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=6.00 in]{demoSignal}
\caption{V$_{pp}$ and DC offset in a typical AC signal. }
\label{fig:demoSignal}
\end{figure}

\section{Laboratory instruction}

\section{Part-A}
\emph{Creating data acquisition program using Matlab data acquisition toolbox}\\
A sample Matlab program is provided in the appendix section of the instruction use that program as the starting point and modify as required. 
\begin{itemize}
\item sample rate to 1000 Hz
\item Sampling  time of 5 seconds
\item Collecting data on  channel 0 of the NI-MyDAQ
\item voltage input range to $\pm$10 Volts.
\end{itemize}

\section{Part-B: Static signal measurement}
\emph{Connect one ``source'' (power supply) to four measurement instrument NI My-DAQ, oscilloscope, hand-held DMM, and table-top DMM}
\begin{itemize}
\item Connect the output of the digital power supply to the breadboard.  Use the breadboard to distribute the source signal to the various measurement devices. The required cables are located on the center column of the lab.
\item From the breadboard, connect the output of the digital power supply to the NI USB-6008 and the oscilloscope. See figure \ref{fig:SSMeas}.
\item From the breadboard, connect the output of the digital power supply to the hand-held and table-top DMMs. See figure \ref{fig:SSMeas}.
\end{itemize}
\begin{figure}[!htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=4.5in]{Lab04Fig01_new.png}
\caption{Sample connection from breadboard to four different measurement instrument.}
\label{fig:SSMeas}
\end{figure}

\section{Part-C: Measure static voltages with four different methods}
\begin{itemize}
\item Vary the power supply voltage from 0 to 5 volts in 1 volt increments.
\item Record the voltage, as accurately and precisely as possible with each instrument, using four methods:
\begin{itemize}
\item	Table-top DMM.
\item	Hand-held DMM.  Pay attention to the input range of the DMM.
\item	Oscilloscope. There is a function for reporting ``average voltage''.
\item	NI data acquisition system. Make sure to display average value to 8 decimal place in the acquisition program 
\end{itemize}
\item	Record all four values for each input voltage, using the most accurate and precise method for each instrument. You will need to log the data in your lab book. 
\item	For your post-lab report, plot voltage error (measured-input) vs. input (from the digital power supply) for all four methods on the same figure. Use markers for your points.
\item	Determine the resolution of each measurement instrument?
\item	Change the time range on the oscilloscope to a very small value.  Is there a dynamic component in the digital source?  What is it from?  Could it be from aliasing?
\end{itemize}
%\begin{wrapfigure}{r}{0.20\textwidth}
%\includegraphics[width=1.25in]{Lab04Fig02.png}
%\caption{BNC T-connector.}
%\label{fig:BNC}
%\end{wrapfigure}
\section{Part-D: Dynamic Signal Measurements}
\emph{Connect one source function generator to two 1) NI My-DAQ, and, 2)oscilloscope).}
\begin{itemize}
\item Disconnect the power supply from the breadboard
\item Connect the output of the function generator to the NI My-DAQ and the oscilloscope. You will need the BNC T-Adapter (T connector located in the resistor kit).  See figure \ref{fig:dynSignal} .
\end{itemize}


\section{Part-D: Measure dynamic signals with two different methods.}
\begin{itemize}
\item Dial in the following AC signal on the function generator: $y(t) =2.5+ 2sin(2 \pi 0.5 t)$
\item	Set the sample rate to 1000 Hz in your data acquisition Matlab script and the sampling time to 5 times the time period of the function $y(t)$. You will have to modify the sampling time for different signals.
\item Use the zoom X-axis button on the oscilloscope to zoom until 2-5 waves are visible. (You may have to modify this for every new signal)
\item Increase the input frequency, the frequency of the function generator $y(t)$, incrementally starting from 0.5 Hz to 1,125 Hz.
\item	Compare the output on the Matlab program with the output displayed on the oscilloscope.  Questions to consider: 
\begin{itemize}
\item Which is better for high-frequency measurements? Calculate the frequency of two acquired signal 
\item For which range of frequencies would you be comfortable using both?
\end{itemize}


\item	For your post-lab, save the acquired data for the following five frequencies of the $y(t)$:
\begin{itemize}
\item A frequency 0.2 times of the Nyquist frequency  the signal begins to ``look'' discretized (below the Nyquist frequency).
\item A frequency 0.9 times of the Nyquist frequency  the signal begins to ``look'' discretized (below the Nyquist frequency).
\item A frequency 1.0 times of the Nyquist frequency  the signal begins to ``look'' discretized or Aliased.
\item A frequency 1.10 times the Nyquist frequency. What is the predicted Alias frequency?  What is the actual?
\item A frequency 2.25 times the Nyquist frequency. What is the predicted Alias frequency?  What is the actual?
\end{itemize}
\item Show your results to TA and make sure you have the all the required data for post-lab. 
\end{itemize}


\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=4.5in]{Lab04Fig02.png}
\caption{Figure showing connection for acquiring dynamic signal.}
\label{fig:dynSignal}
\end{figure}

\section{Part-E}
Return lab space to prior condition
\begin{itemize}
\item Turn off the power supply.
\item Remove wires connecting the power supply to the breadboard and return to the wall
\item Remove all breadboard wires and place them back in the wire kit in an organized fashion.
\item Remove the pendulum wires from the breadboard and set aside.
\item Log off the computer.
\item Make sure to copy the data to your harddrive.
\item {\bf Do this for every lab!}
\end{itemize}

\section{Part-F}
\emph{Post-Laboratory Assignment} \\
For this experiment submit the following items on Canvas for your post-laboratory assessment. Make sure to read the sample code provided for post-lab plotting in sections \ref{app:postLabStat} and \ref{app:postLabDyna}.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Static Voltage Measurement Plot. Submit a single figure with a plot of voltage error (measured minus input) vs. input (from the digital power supply) for all four methods. Use markers for your points, include a legend and labels.
\item Aliasing Figure. Plot the acquired signals in Part D. Use Subplot to create a single figure with 5 plots (5 rows, 1 column). The plot should be 6.5 inches wide and 8.5 inches high. Make sure the plot shows only first 3 to 4 peaks. Make sure to annotate each Subplot with the measured frequency (the actual frequency from the function generator) and the Alias frequency (the frequency recorded). See the sample plot and code. See sample plot in appendix \ref{app:postLabB} (Note that example shows three signals only. You need to modify your code to add  five different signals). Also make sure to change the title on each figure to show correct values of sampling frequency, signal generator frequency, and Acquired data frequency. 
\item Answer all questions in the post-lab assessment on Canvas.
\end{enumerate}

